04801nam a22006735i 9781477307892DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212015txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015006358  a97814773078927 a10.7560/3023852doi  a(DE-B1597)588773  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aF2659.N4bH65 2015 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a305.8009812231 aHordge-Freeman, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Color of Love :bRacial Features, Stigma, and Socialization in Black Brazilian Families /cElizabeth Hordge-Freeman. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The face of a slave -- tPart I Socialization and stigma -- tChapter 1 What’s love got to do with it? Racial stigma and embodied capital -- tChapter 2 Black bodies, white casts: Racializing and gendering bodies -- tChapter 3 Home is where the hurt is: Affective capital, stigma, and racialization -- tPart II Racial socialization and negotiations in public culture -- tChapter 4 Racial fluency: Reading between and beyond the color lines -- tChapter 5 Mind your blackness: Embodied capital and spatial mobility -- tChapter 6 Antiracism in transgressive families -- tConclusion. The ties that bind -- tAppendix A. Research Methods and Positionality -- tAppendix B. Major Interview Topics -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Color Of Love reveals the power of racial hierarchies to infiltrate our most intimate relationships. Delving far deeper than previous sociologists have into the black Brazilian experience, Elizabeth Hordge-Freeman examines the relationship between racialization and the emotional life of a family. Based on interviews and a sixteen-month ethnography of ten working-class Brazilian families, this provocative work sheds light on how families simultaneously resist and reproduce racial hierarchies. Examining race and gender, Hordge-Freeman illustrates the privileges of whiteness by revealing how those with “blacker” features often experience material and emotional hardships. From parental ties, to sibling interactions, to extended family and romantic relationships, the chapters chart new territory by revealing the connection between proximity to whiteness and the distribution of affection within families. Hordge-Freeman also explores how black Brazilian families, particularly mothers, rely on diverse strategies that reproduce, negotiate, and resist racism. She frames efforts to modify racial features as sometimes reflecting internalized racism, and at other times as responding to material and emotional considerations. Contextualizing their strategies within broader narratives of the African diaspora, she examines how Salvador’s inhabitants perceive the history of the slave trade itself in a city that is referred to as the “blackest” in Brazil. She argues that racial hierarchies may orchestrate family relationships in ways that reflect and reproduce racial inequality, but black Brazilian families actively negotiate these hierarchies to assert their citizenship and humanity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBlacksxRace identityzBrazil. 0aBlacksxSocializationzBrazil. 0aBlackszBrazilzSalvadorxSocial conditions. 0aFamilies, BlackzBrazil. 0aRacismzBrazil. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30238540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477307892423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477307892/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aE